# Cursor Rules for Portfolio Site Development

## 🚀 General Code Quality

### Code Standards
- Write clean, readable, maintainable code with consistent formatting and indentation
- Use descriptive variable, function, and class names
- **Naming Conventions:**
  - `camelCase` for variables/functions
  - `PascalCase` for classes/components
  - `UPPER_CASE` for constants
- Keep functions single-responsibility
- Avoid excessive nesting; prefer early returns
- Store secrets/config in `.env` files and never commit them
- Separate frontend (`/client`) and backend (`/server`) code

### Code Structure
```javascript
// ✅ Good: Single responsibility, early return
function validateEmail(email) {
  if (!email) return false;
  if (!email.includes('@')) return false;
  return email.length > 5;
}

// ❌ Bad: Nested conditions
function validateEmail(email) {
  if (email) {
    if (email.includes('@')) {
      if (email.length > 5) {
        return true;
      }
    }
  }
  return false;
}
```

## 📚 Documentation & Comments

### File-Level Documentation
- Add brief file-level description at the top of each file
- Use docstrings for all functions and methods
- Describe purpose, parameters, return values, and side effects
- Add inline comments for non-obvious logic only
- Avoid redundant comments that simply restate code

### Documentation Examples
```javascript
/**
 * Portfolio Site - Main JavaScript File
 * Handles theme switching, smooth scrolling, and form validation
 * @author Muahua Ulysses Vang
 * @version 1.0.0
 */

/**
 * Validates and submits the contact form
 * @param {Event} event - Form submission event
 * @returns {Promise<boolean>} Success status
 */
async function handleContactSubmit(event) {
  // Prevent default form submission
  event.preventDefault();
  
  // Validate form data
  const formData = new FormData(event.target);
  const email = formData.get('email');
  
  if (!isValidEmail(email)) {
    showError('Please enter a valid email address');
    return false;
  }
  
  // ... rest of function
}
```

## 🛡️ Error Handling & Edge Cases

### Input Validation
- Handle invalid inputs and unexpected states gracefully
- Validate data from all external sources
- Use specific exception handling over generic catch-alls
- Provide meaningful error messages

### Error Handling Examples
```javascript
// ✅ Good: Specific error handling
try {
  const response = await fetch('/api/contact', {
    method: 'POST',
    body: JSON.stringify(formData)
  });
  
  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
  }
  
  const result = await response.json();
  return result;
} catch (error) {
  if (error.name === 'TypeError') {
    console.error('Network error:', error.message);
    showError('Network error. Please check your connection.');
  } else {
    console.error('API error:', error.message);
    showError('Something went wrong. Please try again.');
  }
  return false;
}

// ❌ Bad: Generic error handling
try {
  // ... code
} catch (error) {
  console.error(error);
  showError('Error occurred');
}
```

## ⚡ Performance & Efficiency

### Optimization Guidelines
- Optimize for clarity first, then performance
- Use appropriate data structures
- Avoid unnecessary loops or repeated computations
- Use pagination for large datasets
- Implement lazy loading for images and heavy components

### Performance Examples
```javascript
// ✅ Good: Efficient DOM manipulation
const projectCards = document.querySelectorAll('.project-card');
projectCards.forEach(card => {
  const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
    entries.forEach(entry => {
      if (entry.isIntersecting) {
        entry.target.classList.add('animate-in');
        observer.unobserve(entry.target);
      }
    });
  });
  observer.observe(card);
});

// ❌ Bad: Inefficient repeated DOM queries
function animateCards() {
  const cards = document.querySelectorAll('.project-card');
  cards.forEach(card => {
    card.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
      // This creates multiple event listeners
    });
  });
}
```

## 🔒 Security

### Security Standards
- Never hardcode passwords, API keys, or sensitive data
- Sanitize and validate all user inputs
- Use prepared statements or ORM methods for database queries
- Follow secure coding practices for the chosen tech stack
- External links must use `target='_blank'` and `rel='noopener noreferrer'`

### Security Examples
```javascript
// ✅ Good: Secure external links
function createExternalLink(url, text) {
  const link = document.createElement('a');
  link.href = url;
  link.textContent = text;
  link.target = '_blank';
  link.rel = 'noopener noreferrer';
  return link;
}

// ✅ Good: Input sanitization
function sanitizeInput(input) {
  return input
    .trim()
    .replace(/[<>]/g, '') // Remove potential HTML tags
    .substring(0, 1000);  // Limit length
}

// ❌ Bad: Unsafe external links
function createLink(url, text) {
  return `<a href="${url}">${text}</a>`;
}
```

## 🧪 Testing & Maintainability

### Code Quality
- Write unit tests for all critical logic
- Ensure new code passes all existing tests
- Keep code modular and reusable
- Avoid duplicated code by extracting helper functions
- Use consistent error handling patterns

### Maintainability Examples
```javascript
// ✅ Good: Reusable utility functions
const utils = {
  debounce(func, wait) {
    let timeout;
    return function executedFunction(...args) {
      const later = () => {
        clearTimeout(timeout);
        func(...args);
      };
      clearTimeout(timeout);
      timeout = setTimeout(later, wait);
    };
  },
  
  validateEmail(email) {
    const emailRegex = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;
    return emailRegex.test(email);
  },
  
  showNotification(message, type = 'info') {
    const notification = document.createElement('div');
    notification.className = `notification notification-${type}`;
    notification.textContent = message;
    document.body.appendChild(notification);
    
    setTimeout(() => {
      notification.remove();
    }, 3000);
  }
};

// ❌ Bad: Duplicated code
function showSuccess(message) {
  // ... duplicate notification code
}

function showError(message) {
  // ... duplicate notification code
}
```

## 📝 Version Control

### Git Standards
- Use Git with small, meaningful commits
- Follow project branching and pull request guidelines
- Write clear commit messages
- Use conventional commit format

### Commit Message Format
```
type(scope): description

feat(contact): add form validation and submission
fix(navigation): resolve mobile menu toggle issue
docs(readme): update deployment instructions
style(css): improve button hover animations
refactor(js): extract utility functions to separate module
test(validation): add unit tests for email validation
```

## 🎨 Frontend – Portfolio Page

### Design Standards
- Use mobile-first responsive design
- Optimize images and lazy-load heavy components
- Maintain consistent color palette, typography, and spacing
- Use semantic HTML
- Break UI into reusable components with clear names
- Minimize inline CSS; prefer CSS modules, styled-components, or Tailwind

### Portfolio Requirements
- **About Section**: Personal introduction, skills, experience
- **Projects Showcase**: Each project must have:
  - Title
  - Description
  - Technologies used
  - Live demo link
  - GitHub link
- **Contact Form**: Must validate inputs and provide success/error feedback

### Component Structure
```javascript
// ✅ Good: Reusable component structure
class ProjectCard {
  constructor(project) {
    this.project = project;
    this.element = this.createCard();
  }
  
  createCard() {
    const card = document.createElement('article');
    card.className = 'project-card';
    card.innerHTML = `
      <h3>${this.project.title}</h3>
      <p>${this.project.description}</p>
      <div class="technologies">
        ${this.project.technologies.map(tech => 
          `<span class="tech-tag">${tech}</span>`
        ).join('')}
      </div>
      <div class="project-links">
        <a href="${this.project.demo}" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          Live Demo
        </a>
        <a href="${this.project.github}" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          GitHub
        </a>
      </div>
    `;
    return card;
  }
}
```

## 🔧 Backend – Functionality

### Architecture Standards
- Organize code into controllers, services, models, and routes
- Follow RESTful API conventions
- Keep functions small and single-purpose
- Use ORM or parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Validate all incoming data
- Implement database migration scripts

### Security & Authentication
- Use secure authentication (JWT, OAuth, or session-based)
- Hash passwords with bcrypt or Argon2
- Rate-limit sensitive endpoints
- Standardize API responses

### API Response Format
```javascript
// Standard API response format
{
  success: boolean,
  message: string,
  data?: any,
  timestamp: string,
  statusCode: number
}

// Example responses
{
  success: true,
  message: "Contact form submitted successfully",
  data: { id: "contact_123" },
  timestamp: "2024-01-15T10:30:00Z",
  statusCode: 201
}

{
  success: false,
  message: "Invalid email format",
  data: null,
  timestamp: "2024-01-15T10:30:00Z",
  statusCode: 400
}
```

## 🔗 Full-Stack Integration

### API Standards
- Maintain documented API contract between frontend and backend
- Document API endpoints in README or with Swagger/OpenAPI
- Configure CORS securely, only allowing necessary origins
- Test all frontend API calls before deployment

### CORS Configuration
```javascript
// ✅ Good: Secure CORS configuration
app.use(cors({
  origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGINS?.split(',') || [
    'https://muahuavang.github.io',
    'http://localhost:3000'
  ],
  methods: ['GET', 'POST'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Content-Type', 'Authorization'],
  credentials: true
}));

// ❌ Bad: Open CORS
app.use(cors());
```

## 📋 Code Review Checklist

Before committing code, ensure:
- [ ] Code follows naming conventions
- [ ] Functions are single-responsibility
- [ ] Error handling is implemented
- [ ] Input validation is in place
- [ ] Security best practices are followed
- [ ] Performance considerations are addressed
- [ ] Documentation is complete
- [ ] Tests pass (if applicable)
- [ ] No sensitive data is exposed
- [ ] Code is modular and reusable

## 🚨 Common Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- ❌ Hardcoded credentials or API keys
- ❌ Generic error messages
- ❌ Inline styles in HTML
- ❌ Duplicated code blocks
- ❌ Deeply nested conditionals
- ❌ Unvalidated user inputs
- ❌ Unsafe external links
- ❌ Large, monolithic functions
- ❌ Missing error handling
- ❌ Inconsistent naming conventions

